  "standardBio": "Rootling, titled among keepers as “Thorntrail Trickster,” carries patient growth in every movement. Native to Elderwood Forest, the species unfurls through moss and saplight, leaving traces that other Riftlings can follow like soft maps. Wild groups form loose bonds rather than rigid packs; a shy individual may become the emotional center of a small hearthline. They eat Groveleaf eagerly and dislike food that smells of neglect or spoilage. Ancient keepers carved Rootling silhouettes into travel stones, believing the species guided the lost. Modern hatcheries record them as reliable companions; their social intelligence tuned to group moods makes training feel like conversation. Their signature ability, Rootling's Thorn Whip, reflects a life shaped by Elderwood Forest more than by arena ambition. Many assume Rootlings are aggressive because of their grove affinity; most are cautious first. Young Rootlings practice Rootling's Thorn Whip as play long before they understand battle. Adults teach by demonstration: where to rest, what to avoid, how to share warmth or shade.",
  "fullLore": "Rootlings first condensed from residual rootwhisper along the living edges of Elderwood Forest after early Rift fractures cooled into weather. Their eggs appear where moss and saplight gathers into stillness—never in the loudest danger, always in the pocket of calm beside it. Early surveyors mistook them for ambient phenomena until a Rootling returned a dropped lantern, carefully, as if returning a promise.\n\nIn ancient eras, regional peoples treated Rootlings as omen-bearers rather than pets. Carvings show them walking ahead of caravans, pausing at unstable ground, and curling around children during ashfall or fog. The species was never “tamed” in the old sense; it chose. That choice culture survives in modern Riftkeeper etiquette: you do not yank a Rootling into a bond. You invite, wait, and keep the invitation honest.\n\nModern history is quieter and more practical. Hatcheries map Rootling care cycles with the same seriousness given to rare lines, because common does not mean shallow. Elderwood Forest still holds wild populations that trade soft greetings with passerby pets. After major Rift events, Rootlings often appear first at recovery centers—not as heroes, but as inventory clerks of comfort, counting who is cold, hungry, or afraid.\n\nNatural behavior is shy at the core and adaptable at the edges. They are photosynthetic and season-aware, companion-sized, easy to cradle, and communicate through tap-codes on stone or wood. Socially, they prefer small trusted circles; strangers are assessed by scent, posture, and whether a keeper’s voice stays kind under stress. Intelligence presents as social intelligence tuned to group moods. They sleep in shallow scrapes and prefer weather that matches their affinity’s comfort band.\n\nEcologically, Rootlings act as cleanup foragers within Elderwood Forest. Allies often include Bramblefox and Elderfern; rivalries with Quartzhorn and Hearthstone are usually about nesting space or shiny refuse, not blood feuds. Predators are rare—most threats come from collapsing terrain and careless machines rather than jaws.\n\nCulture around them is affectionate and slightly superstitious. An old keeper journal swears a Rootling refused to leave an injured stranger until dawn warmth returned. Collectors prize unusual cosmetics, yet marketplace notes remind buyers that verified care history matters more than glitter. The common misunderstanding remains: Many assume Rootlings are aggressive because of their grove affinity; most are cautious first. The hidden truth keepers debate in soft rooms is simpler and stranger: Rootlings can hear micro-fractures in Riftstone as a pressure change behind the ears.\n\nFrom egg to evolved form, their life story stays continuous. Eggs look like glazed stones veined with grove light. Hatchlings are clumsy with sincerity; adults become specialists of place; evolved stages sharpen instinct without erasing childhood habits. Battle tendencies favor enduring defense, and evolution philosophy insists transformation should answer lived experience—not fashion.\n\nFor Riftkeepers, a Rootling is a living chapter of Elderwood Forest. Feed it Groveleaf, respect its shy tempo, and it will teach you the region’s quieter grammar: which winds lie, which stones remember, which silences are safe. Personal quests often begin with a shell symbol, a remembered scent, or a dream of a door that only opens when the bond is honest. That is the Rootling bargain—not destiny sold at rarity price, but a life that continues because you showed up.",
